{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <header class="space-y-2">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white tracking-tight">Theme Customization &amp; Architecture</h1>
        <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 text-lg">
            Understand the separation between Rhapsody's core views and your application's custom themes.
            Learn how to safely override, extend, or completely replace the default design system.
        </p>
    </header>

    <hr class="border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800">
    
    <h1>Theming &amp; Customisation</h1>
    <p>
        Rhapsody makes it easy to create custom themes or override the default design.
        All theme files live in the project’s <code>/views/themes/</code> directory – <strong>not</strong> inside <code>/app/views/</code> or the core package.
    </p>
    <p>
        The framework uses <strong>Tailwind CSS v4.3</strong> for the default design. If you extend the core theme, you inherit these styles automatically.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Theme Directory Structure</h2>
    <p>
        The active theme is determined by the <code>APP_THEME</code> environment variable in your <code>.env</code> file.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">APP_THEME=my_custom_theme</code></pre>
    <p>
        If <code>APP_THEME</code> is not set, the framework falls back to the <code>default</code> theme.
    </p>
    <p>
        The themes directory is located at:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">/views/themes/
├── default/               ← fallback theme (always present)
│   ├── layouts/
│   │   └── main.twig
│   ├── home/
│   └── errors/
├── my_custom_theme/       ← your active theme
│   ├── layouts/
│   │   └── main.twig      ← custom layout (optional)
│   ├── home/
│   └── errors/
└── ...</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Extending the Core Theme</h2>
    <p>
        If you want to keep the framework’s default design (Tailwind styling, layout structure, and helpers) but change specific parts, you can <strong>extend</strong> the core templates.
    </p>
    <p>
        Use the <code>@core</code> namespace in your Twig templates to reference core views. For example:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">{{ '{%' }} extends "@core/layouts/main.twig" {{ '%}' }}

{{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;!-- Your custom content here --&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}</code></pre>
    <p>
        This approach inherits the core layout, styles, and global variables (like <code>base_url</code>, <code>auth</code>, <code>flash</code>, etc.). You can override any block defined in the core layout.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-blue-100 border-l-4 border-blue-500 text-blue-700 p-4">
        <strong>Tip:</strong> The core design uses <strong>Tailwind CSS v4.3</strong>. If you extend <code>@core/layouts/main.twig</code>, you automatically get these styles and the Vite asset pipeline.
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Core Views – A Limited Fallback</h2>
    <p>
        The framework core ships with only a <strong>small set of views</strong>:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Documentation pages (<code>@core/docs/...</code>)</li>
        <li>Authentication pages (login, register) – accessible as <code>auth/login.twig</code>, etc.</li>
        <li>Error pages (404, 500) – accessible as <code>errors/404.twig</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        These are available as a fallback <strong>only</strong> for those specific pages. If you render any other view (e.g., <code>home/index.twig</code>) and it does not exist in your active theme or the default theme, the framework <strong>will not</strong> look in the core for it. Instead, Twig will throw a <code>LoaderError</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>You are responsible for providing all the views your application needs</strong> – either in your active theme or the default theme. The core is <em>not</em> a complete view library.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Overriding Core Templates</h2>
    <p>
        To override any of the core‑provided views (login, register, error pages, etc.), simply create a file with the <strong>same relative path</strong> inside your active theme.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, to override the default 404 error page, create:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">/views/themes/my_custom_theme/errors/404.twig</code></pre>
    <p>
        The framework will use your version instead of the core one. You don’t need to use <code>@core</code> when overriding – the loader checks your theme first.
    </p>
    <p>
        The search order for any template is:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Active theme</strong> – <code>/views/themes/{{ APP_THEME }}/</code></li>
        <li><strong>Default theme</strong> – <code>/views/themes/default/</code></li>
        <li><strong>Core views</strong> – <em>only for the specific pages listed above</em> (via <code>@core</code> namespace or fallback)</li>
    </ol>

    <hr>

    <h2>Creating a Completely Custom Theme (From Scratch)</h2>
    <p>
        If you want a <strong>totally custom design</strong> that does <em>not</em> rely on the framework’s default styles or layout, you can build your own parent template.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>Do <strong>not</strong> use <code>@core</code> in your templates.</li>
        <li>Create your own <code>layouts/main.twig</code> inside your theme.</li>
        <li>Include your own CSS (e.g., via <code>&lt;link&gt;</code> tags, or use your own build tool).</li>
        <li>You are responsible for providing the necessary global Twig variables (like <code>base_url</code>, <code>auth</code>, <code>flash</code>) if you need them – they are still available globally, but you must output them as needed.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Example custom <code>main.twig</code>:</p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;My Custom Site&lt;/title&gt;
    &lt;link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ base_url }}/css/my-styles.css"&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;header&gt;My Header&lt;/header&gt;
    {{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;footer&gt;My Footer&lt;/footer&gt;
    &lt;script src="{{ base_url }}/js/app.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
        You can then extend your own layout in any child template:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">{{ '{%' }} extends "layouts/main.twig" {{ '%}' }}
{{ '{%' }} block content {{ '%}' }}
    &lt;!-- custom content --&gt;
{{ '{%' }} endblock {{ '%}' }}</code></pre>

    <hr>

    <h2>Adding View Namespaces</h2>
    <p>
        If you have reusable template components (e.g., from a module), you can add custom Twig namespaces in <code>bootstrap.php</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">$loader->addPath('/path/to/module/views', 'module');</code></pre>
    <p>Then render: <code>$this->view('@module/index.twig')</code>.</p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Extend core</strong> → use <code>@core</code> and override blocks (inherits Tailwind design).</li>
        <li><strong>Override a core template</strong> → place a file with the same path in your active theme (for login, register, errors).</li>
        <li><strong>Build a custom theme from scratch</strong> → create your own <code>layouts/main.twig</code> and avoid <code>@core</code>.</li>
        <li>All theme files live in <code>/views/themes/</code>.</li>
        <li>The core design is built with <strong>Tailwind CSS v4.3</strong>.</li>
        <li>Core views are <strong>limited</strong> – only documentation, auth, and errors. For all other views, you must provide them yourself.</li>
    </ul>
{% endblock %}